options.optiontext: Owning things is freedom. Until the things own me
I embrace technology, but my fridge now judges my eating habits
Friendships are priceless, but I seem to be paying for them more often
I work hard today, hoping future me finally gets a break
My financial plan is simple: don’t die before I can afford to retire
My phone does everything for me—except give me time away from my phone
Networking events feel like auditions for friendships with an entry fee
Life’s purpose? To make enough money so I can stop thinking about money
Success means having options. Right now, my option is instant noodles or tap water
Technology makes life easier. Except for the part where I never stop working.
I love my family, but our WhatsApp group is just emergency expenses
Money can’t buy happiness, but it does make unhappiness more comfortable
Owning assets means stability, but I spend most of my time paying for them
Every app promises to save me time, yet I have none left
Friendship is worth more than money, but money makes friendship easier
I trade my time for money, hoping one day I can trade money for time
